Goal of this markdown: Using a mixed model approach to analyze my evironmental and field data. I am addressing research question #3:
Is variation in salinity, air temperature, or pH associated with changes in abundances or reproductive effort of F. distichus populations in SFE? –> compare models and see which ones have the most evidence (based on fit of model and evidence)
- since there’s no random factor, I went back to liner models instead of mixed linear models
- assumptions: environmental variables matter (lit evidence and prior knowledge)
- Environmental variables have been filtered for tides

Questions for Karina:
- Want to talk through the parameters I picked for the research questions below
- Need help with interaction terms - Really not sure about any of the fits
- oogonia/thalli model needs to be transformed but can I still use square root transformation since it’s not strictly count data?
- Not sure how to rank terms using AIC, most of what I’m seeing is to rank different models, not terms within a model

Research Questions:

Juvenile abundance and environmental conditions

  1. Is juvenile adudance affected by extreme salinity events?
    For models:
    1.1 Is juvenile density affected by daily maximum salinities less than 10? 1.2 Is juvenile density affected by daily minimum salities great than 28?

  2. Is juvenile abundance affected by extreme heat? For models:
    2.1 Is juvenile density affected by daily maximum air temperatures greater than 26C?

  3. Is juvenile abundance affected by pH?
    For models:
    3.1 Is juvenile density affected by daily maximum pH less than 8?

Adult reproduction, pH, and salinity 1. Is adult reproduction affected by low salintiy and and low pH? For models:
1.1 Is oogonia per thalli affected by daily maximum salinity less than 10? 1.2 Is oogonia per thalli affected by daily maximum pH less than 8? –> I think I should have both of these terms in one model

(thinking through research questions, defined better above) 1. Juvenile abundance:
- j.abundance ~ salinity at high tide –> interested in extreme events both high and low –> daily max less than 10 and daily min greater than 28

  • j.abundance ~ air temp at low tide (max daily air temp) –> interested in higher temperatures –> daily min greater than 80F

  • j.abundance ~ pH at high tide -> interested in lower pH –> daily max less than 8

  • how to pick metric: because of x work, we picked this or (if no lit) we’re to test these or it’s likely that this affects. Look at lit

  • j.abundance ~ salinity + air temp + interaction term?

  • Run all these models, AIC ranking with most evidence at top

  1. Adult thalli:
  • Although we didn’t see any seasonlity, we’re still curious about the affects of ph and salinity on repro –> oogonia per thalli (individual level) think about why you only picked that one
  • interested in low salinity (daily max less than 10) and low pH (daily max less than 8)

Notes from 6/11 meeting:
- not using site as a term since the difference in sites is really refelcted of envirnomental differences and it’d be redundant to do both –> multicolinear, predicting similar responses - not using week number as term. Similar as site, differences in enviromental factors according to week number can be attributed to seasonal differences and would be redundant. Perhaps seasonality but not yet –>multicolinear, predicting similar responses - y ~ all the terms, then AIC to rank different parameters

Read in data

#read in data
all<-read.csv(
      "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Cmwegener/thesis/master/data/environment_field/envi.field.all.csv",
    header = TRUE
  )
all$date<-as.Date(all$date, format = c("%Y-%m-%d"))

Convert date to number of weeks of surveys. Starting at week 0 being the first survey. This will make it a contiuous variable and then I can add a quadratic term to it. This is different that “week number of the year” so I have to use a customized approach. I was able to find a similar question online: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/54406803/assigning-custom-week-number-in-r/54407091, https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19780415/lubridate-week-to-find-consecutive-week-number-for-multi-year-periods

# subtracts minimun week number, "+0" sets what week you want to start it on
all$week_nr <- (interval(min(all$date), all$date) %/% weeks(1)) + 0
